DESCRIPTION: While the 65 foot high ceilings are timeless, the projected 3D entertainment is the finest of modernity.
TITLE: The Grand Hall

DESCRIPTION: Relax in the lobby, grab a drink at the Lobby Bar, or take a closer look at the stunning Tiffany window.
TITLE: The Midway

DESCRIPTION: The Station Grille continues to charm guests in the grand tradition of showman and hotelier Fred Harvey.
TITLE: Dining in Style

DESCRIPTION: From Executive Rooms, to packages targeted for leisure travelers such as Romanic Getaways and AAA members: there is something for every guest.
TITLE: Gorgeous Guestrooms

DESCRIPTION: The 305 guestrooms and suites have been restored to their original 1919 grandeur, while maintain the height of luxury that guests expect today.

TITLE: Meetings and Events

TITLE: Terrace with a View

DESCRIPTION: Located in the center of the city, the Fort Shelby Doubletree is the perfect place to base your Detroit vacation.

TITLE: The Round Robin Bar

DESCRIPTION: Check out the fitness center or book a treatment at the Red Door Spa.

TITLE: Heart of Houston

DESCRIPTION: The Sam Houston can host an event of any kind for your group or gathering up to 175 guests.
TITLE: Mockingbird Board Room

DESCRIPTION: This popular bar boasts a variety of unique premium spirits, bourbons, single malt scotches, and cognacs.
TITLE: The Sam Bar Houston

DESCRIPTION: Historic Houston merely steps away, the Sam Houston is the perfect starting point for a getaway to the city.
TITLE: The Lobby

DESCRIPTION: The 44 suites and rooms that make up the Inn at Diamond Cove combine luxurious comfort for guests with the unique style of a New England Inn.
TITLE: Comfortable Accomodations

DESCRIPTION: Diamond Cove is the resort community of the historic Great Diamond Island.  Guests can enjoy boating from the marina, hiking the island, a fitness room and Maine Island Yoga.
TITLE: Great Diamond Island

DESCRIPTION: All suites feature a fireplace, parlor and a separate dining room, while the Inn features an outdoor pool with a Cabana Bar.
TITLE: Maine R&R

DESCRIPTION: The Diamond's Edge Restaurant is convenient to the Marina and serves guests and visitors traditional New England favorites and fine seafood.
TITLE: New England Dining

DESCRIPTION: The intimate size of the Inn guarantees that your special event or meeting will be personal and memorable.
TITLE: Banquets and Events

DESCRIPTION: The Ashland Springs Hotel is the perfect origin point to experience the Oregon Chocolate Festival and the Oregon Shakespeare Festival.
TITLE: Festivals

DESCRIPTION: A view of the Sandy Point State Park Lighthouse.
SUBTITLE: Sandy Point
TITLE: Sandy Point State Park

DESCRIPTION: Dining at Graylyn caters to all appetites. The Grille room pictured here is the perfect place to sit in front of the fire and enjoy a cocktail.
TITLE: The Graylyn Grille Room

DESCRIPTION: Restored fully in 2012 The Mews features 35 guestrooms as well as breakout meeting space for a totally unique event.
TITLE: Entry to the Mews

DESCRIPTION: Guests are welcome to enjoy rooms and suites in a number of different buildings including the original Manor House which dates from the 1930s.
TITLE: Luxurious Accomodations

DESCRIPTION: The 55 acres of The Graylyn estate are the perfect place to step back in time while still experiencing the most modern hospitality.
TITLE: Explore the Grounds

DESCRIPTION: As an International Conference Center Graylyn has hosted luminaries including four Presidents and 13 international delegations.
TITLE: Where History Happened

DESCRIPTION: Graylyn Dining is a 4 course experience that is created nightly by the culinary team.  you don’t want to miss.
TITLE: Exquisite Dining

DESCRIPTION: The Plaza is home to the only Vinotherapie Spa in the United States, boasting 14 treatment rooms and a world-famous menu of treatments featuring grape and vine active patents.
TITLE: Caudalie Vinotherapie Spa

DESCRIPTION: New York City is literally outside your door at The Plaza Hotel0 located in the heart of Manhattan at Fifth Avenue at Central Park South.
TITLE: The City that Never Sleeps

DESCRIPTION: The attention to detail is legendary at The Plaza.  For example, did you know that The Plaza is the first hotel in the world to have 24-carat gold plated Sherle Wagner designed sinks and fixtures in every guestroom?
TITLE: Royal Treatment

DESCRIPTION: Each of the 19 rooms have a unique feel- guaranteeing a personal experience for each guest.
TITLE: Charming Rooms

DESCRIPTION: The many guestrooms and suites take their inspiration from notable names and famous guests, such as Fred Astaire and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
TITLE: All in the Name

DESCRIPTION: The many courses at The American Club have made history time and time again through the many cups and championships that have been held on site.
TITLE: Golf

DESCRIPTION: The glorious gardens of Kohler were brought to life by Walter Kohler Sr. who took his inspiration from the great garden cities of Europe in 1913.
TITLE: The Gardens of Kohler

DESCRIPTION: For special getaways, the American Club also offers accommodations in the adults-only Carriage House.
TITLE: The Carriage House

DESCRIPTION: Families of all shapes and sizes will find adventure at The American Club- ranging from junior golf, hikes, boat rentals, horseback riding and much more.
TITLE: Outdoor Adventures

DESCRIPTION: Famous guests to the Seelbach have included Billy Joel, Miss America, and several United States Presidents.
TITLE: Lobby

DESCRIPTION: After taking a walk through historic Louisville, guests can take advantage of the state of the art fitness center.
TITLE: Indoor and Outdoor Adventures

DESCRIPTION: Al Capone was a frequent guest of the Seelbach during the Roaring 20s.  His favorite room even featured two hidden doors which led to secret passageways for a quick getaway.
TITLE: A Secret History

DESCRIPTION: With views of downtown Louisville and modern amenities, each guestroom at The Seelbach combines history with comfort.
TITLE: Deluxe Accomodations

DESCRIPTION: Over 25,000 visitors were part of the opening festivities in May of 1905.
TITLE: State of the Art

DESCRIPTION: While stationed with the US Army nearby, F. Scott Fitzgerald spent his weekends enjoying the Seelbach.  Rumor has it he took the character of Gatsby from gangster George Remus, who used to frequent the Louisville hotspot.
TITLE: Concierge Lounge

DESCRIPTION: The historic Seelbach has been showcased in several feature films, as recently as 2013's The Great Gatsby.
TITLE: Grand History

DESCRIPTION: The stones used to make up the foundations, as well as the large fireplaces was obtained from out of use walls on the grounds of Bear Mountain State Park.
TITLE: Exterior

DESCRIPTION: Legend says that the Mizpah is visited often by the Lady in Red, a once popular lady of the evening who was known to frequent the hotel in the early 1900s.
TITLE: Spirited Visitors

TITLE: Historic Building

DESCRIPTION: The 48 guestrooms within the Mizpah offer historic touches with modern conveniences such as free parking and complimentary Internet.
TITLE: Luxury Accommodations

DESCRIPTION: Their are activities for the whole family both inside the hotel and outside in historic Portland.
TITLE: Game Room

DESCRIPTION: The perfect home away from home, with a range of amenities such as microwaves, flexible work/dining spaces, and the most modern technology.
TITLE: Guestroom

DESCRIPTION: Step into the doors that have welcomed Jimmy Stewart, Rudolph Valentino, Queen Marie of Romania and every President from Theodore Roosevelt to Richard Nixon.
TITLE: Lobby

DESCRIPTION: In addition to the family friendly pool, there is also a fitness room and video arcade available for those rainy days.
TITLE: Pool

DESCRIPTION: All of Portland is just steps away, including Washington Park.
TITLE: Room with a View

DESCRIPTION: Dinner at Portland Prime is the perfect way to end an evening, but if you are on your way out, visit the Complimentary Evening Reception.
TITLE: Wine & Dine

DESCRIPTION: The historic hotel is over 100 years old, but the 49 rooms and suites boast the modern luxury and comfort.
TITLE: Guestroom

DESCRIPTION: Step back into this National Register building and heart of the town at Wise.

DESCRIPTION: Just a short distance away from University of Virginia's College at Wise, the staff are happy to arrange events from small board meetings to celebratory banquets.

DESCRIPTION: From the individually themed suites to the local attractions such as Kendrick Park and a Buffalo pasture, families are sure to have an immersive experience here.
TITLE: Family Adventure

DESCRIPTION: Each and every suite has a themed feel in honor of its namesake.  Give each one a close viewing, then return year after year to your favorite.

The Monitor's turret breaks the surface of the water for the first time in 140 years.
A full-sized replica of the USS Monitor can be seen at the The Mariners' Museum, the official visitor center for Monitor NMS, in Newport News, Virginia.
The remains of two Monitor sailors found inside the turret in 2002 were buried at Arlington National Cemetery on March 8, 2013.
In 2002, U.S. Navy divers prepared the turret for lift. As the turret was excavated, the remains of two sailors were found inside.
NOAA diver on the wreck site of the USS Monitor

Historic image of the USS Monitor crew taken July 9, 1862, while the ship was docked on the James River in Virginia. The Monitor, a Civil War ironclad, is famous for fighting the CSS Virginia in the Battle of Hampton Road and for changing naval warfare forever.

DESCRIPTION: Most visitors do not have the opportunity to see the closed front gate. The gate depicts the swordfight between American Lieutenant Colonel William Washington and British Lieutenant Colonel Banastre Tarleton and his officers. The gate is based on the William Ranney painting of the Battle of Cowpens, which shows Washington's servant saving Washington's life by firing a pistol at a British officer.
SUBTITLE: Iron gate depicting British and American cavalrymen swordfight
TITLE: Front Gate at Cowpens National Battlefield

DESCRIPTION: Around 1828, Robert Scruggs built this cabin for his wife and himself. The couple had eleven children, and as the family grew, they added rooms onto the house and covered the log walls with paneling. In doing so, they preserved the original walls of the cabin within the additions. The cabin remained in the family until the mid-1970s, when the National Park Service purchased the property and began restoration.
SUBTITLE: Blue skies and green trees changing colors provide the backdrop for the Robert Scruggs House.
TITLE: The Robert Scruggs House

DESCRIPTION:
The Visitor Center Museum contains a 3-pounder cannon, other weapons of the Revolutionary War period, paintings and exhibits.

"Cowpens: A Battle Remembered" is a laser disk presentation shown hourly in the museum.  The 18 minute show was filmed off site during the 225th anniversary of the battle and depicts the events of the battle.

Fiber-optic Map Display illustrates the Southern Campaign of the American Revolution and the battle tactics employed by Daniel Morgan at Cowpens.  (13 minutes)

Sales Outlet operated by Eastern National offers books, posters, postcards, slides, and theme-related souvenirs for purchase.
SUBTITLE: Cowpens National Battlefield Visitor Center with blue sky and fluffy clouds
TITLE: Cowpens National Battlefield Visitor Center

DESCRIPTION: The visitor center at Agate Fossil Beds National Monument was built in 1992.  It houses exhibits describing the Miocene mammal fossils found nearby in the late 1890s, the historic excavations as well as the James H. Cook Gallery.  The gallery features American Indian artifacts which resulted from a friendship between rancher James Cook and Red Cloud of the Oglala Lakota Sioux.
SUBTITLE: Agate Fossil Beds National Monument Visitor Center
TITLE: The visitor center at Agate Fossil Beds National Monument

DESCRIPTION: These two hills were the destination of many paleontologists who excavated mammal fossils in the early 1900s.  They found a huge bonebed comprised of thousands of fossils from mainly a small rhino called Menoceras.  Also found were strange critters with names like Daeodon and Moropus.
SUBTITLE: The Agate Fossil Hills where the mammal fossils were found.
TITLE: The Agate Fossil Hills, University on the left and Carnegie on the right.

DESCRIPTION: Life-size skeletons and a reconsturcted bonebed are the key elements of the diorama in the main room of the visitor center.  The bones were cast from the actual fossils that were found in the Agate Hills framed by the windows.  This diorama tells the story of the death scene and the creation of the bonebed some 20 million years ago.
SUBTITLE: This large diorama is the focus of the fossil displays in the visitor center.
TITLE: The Miocene death scene diorama.

DESCRIPTION: In the early 1900s, paleontologists from many museums and universities worked in the Fossil Hills quarries and took huge slabs of the bonebed home with them to study.
SUBTITLE: Slab of the Great Bonebed of Agate excavated from Carnegie Hill.
TITLE: The Great Bonebed of Agate

DESCRIPTION: The James H. Cook Gallery resulted from a friendship between James Cook and Red Cloud of the Oglala Lakota Sioux.  Many of the items in the collection are important artifacts such as Red Cloud's shirt and three generations of pipebags.  There are also many items that were made for members of the Cook family.
SUBTITLE: Inside the James H. Cook Gallery
TITLE: The Red Cloud shirt exhibit in the James H. Cook Gallery.

DESCRIPTION: This wintercount was painted by Dawn Little Sky from the Pine Ridge Reservation for Agate Fossil Beds in 1990.  Using events from actual Lakota wintercounts and events that affected the Lakota, the Cooks and all of us she put an extensive history lesson on an elk hide.  This hide hangs in the entrance room of the James H. Cook Collection.
SUBTITLE: The Running Water Winter Count.
TITLE: The Running Water Wintercount in the entrance room for the James H. Cook Gallery.

DESCRIPTION: It was in the parlor of the McLean House that General Lee surrendered the Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865.
SUBTITLE: The McLean House where General Lee surrendered to General Grant
TITLE: The McLean House where General Lee surrendered to General Grant

DESCRIPTION: It is confusing that the name of the entire village is Appomattox Court House because the famous Lee-Grant meeting happened in the McLean House, in the village of Appomattox Court House.  There is though a courthouse building that today houses the park Visitor Center, but it is not where the surrender happened.  Hint: Court House, two words is a town, courthouse, one word is a building.
SUBTITLE: The courthouse building serves as the park Visitor Center today.
TITLE: The courthouse building serves as the park Visitor Center today.

DESCRIPTION: The ca. 1820 Tavern Kitchen serves as the park bookstore today.  This store is run by Eastern National and a portion of the profits come back to park to support educational programming.  Here visitors can purchase books, postcards, and novelty items specific to Appomattox Court House.
SUBTITLE: The park bookstore is located in the Clover Hill Tavern Kitchen building.
TITLE: The park bookstore is located in the Clover Hill Tavern Kitchen building.

DESCRIPTION: The Living History Program at the park typically runs during the summer months.  There are several people that lived in the village in 1865 that are portrayed.  These interpreters speak as though it is still 1865 and can provide visitors their version of what happened here "just a few months ago" and what it means to them.
SUBTITLE: First person Living History programs provide fascinating perspectives of the surrender story.
TITLE: First person Living History programs provide fascinating perspectives of the surrender story.

DESCRIPTION: Inside the Clover Hill Tavern on April 10, 1865, Federal soldiers printed 30,000 parole passes that would be filled out and issued to nearly all of the soldiers serving under General Lee at Appomattox.  Today, particularly during the summer months, visitors can see printing demonstrations of how the passes were made on hand cranked military presses.
SUBTITLE: Parole passes for the Confederate soldiers were printed in the Clover Hill Tavern.
TITLE: Parole passes for the Confederate soldiers were printed in the Clover Hill Tavern where printing demos are still done today.

DESCRIPTION: Every April the Laying down of Arms ceremony is recreated on a small scale.  It was originally done on April 12, 1865 and was what was required of the Confederates in order to be paroled and allowed to go home.
SUBTITLE: Each April, the Laying Down of Arms ceremony is recreated on a small scale in the village.
TITLE: Each April, the Laying Down of Arms ceremony is recreated on a small scale in the village.

DESCRIPTION: The five cases consolidated as Brown v. Board of Education were deliberately drawn from different areas of the country. Emphasis on the South would have introduced political complications to an already complex case. Topeka, Kansas was chosen as the lead case for the same reason. African American schools in Topeka were essentially equal to the white schools, so segregation itself, not equlaity, would be the issue in the question.

DESCRIPTION: On May 4, 1987, Monroe Elementary School achieved National Historic Landmark designation for its significance to the Brown v. Board of Education U.S. Supreme Court case. DESCRIPTION: Approximately $11 million was needed to rehabilitate the former Monroe School into its current usage as Brown v. Board of Education National Historic Site. DESCRIPTION: The Great House with its surrounding neighbors of other earthern ruins is an icon in the desert near Coolidge, Arizona. DESCRIPTION:
The structure we now call John Brown's Fort was erected in 1848 as the Armory's fire engine and guard house. The building was described in a June 30, 1848, Armory report: "An engine and guard-house, 35½ x 24 feet, one story brick, covered with slate, and having copper gutters and down spouts, has been constructed, and is now occupied." It was in this building that John Brown and several of his followers barricaded themselves during the final hours of their ill-fated raid of October 16, 17, and 18, 1859.

John Brown's Fort, as the structure became known, was the only Armory building to escape destruction during the Civil War. In 1891, the fort was sold, dismantled and transported to Chicago where it was displayed a short distance from The World's Columbian Exposition. The building, attracting only 11 visitors in ten days, was closed, dismantled again and left on a vacant lot.

In 1894, Washington, D.C. journalist Kate Field, who had a keen interest in preserving memorabilia of John Brown, spearheaded a campaign to return the fort to Harpers Ferry. Local resident Alexander Murphy made five acres available to Miss Field, and the Baltimore & Ohio Railroad offered to ship the disassembled fort to Harpers Ferry free of charge. In 1895, John Brown's Fort was rebuilt on the Murphy Farm about three miles outside of town on a bluff overlooking the Shenandoah River.

In 1903, Storer College began their own fundraising drive to acquire the structure. In 1909, on the occasion of the 50th Anniversary of John Brown's Raid, the building was purchased and moved to the Storer College campus on Camp Hill in Harpers Ferry. 

Acquired by the National Park Service in 1960, the building was moved back to the Lower Town in 1968. Because the fort's original site was covered with a railroad embankment in 1894, the building now sits about 150 feet east of its original location.
SUBTITLE: John Brown's Fort in the Lower Town portion of Harpers Ferry
TITLE: John Brown's Fort

DESCRIPTION:
Thomas Jefferson stood here on October 25, 1783 and described the view as he saw it:

"The passage of the Patowmac through the Blue Ridge is perhaps one of the most stupendous scenes in Nature. You stand on a very high point of land. On your right comes up the Shenandoah, having ranged along the foot of the mountain a hundred miles to seek a vent. On your left approaches the Patowmac in quest of a passage also. In the moment of their junction they rush together against the mountain, rend it asunder and pass off to the sea. The first glance of this scene hurries our senses into the opinion that this earth has been created in time, that the mountains were formed first, that the rivers began to flow afterwards, that in this place particularly they have been so dammed up by the Blue Ridge of mountains as to have formed an ocean which filled the whole valley; that, continuing to rise, they have at last broken over at this spot and have torn the mountain down from its summit to its base. The piles of rock on each hand, but particularly on the Shenandoah, the evident marks of their disruptions and avulsions from their beds by the most powerful agents in nature, corroborate the impression.

"But the distant finishing which nature has given the picture is of a very different character. It is a true contrast to the former. It is as placid and delightful as that is wild and tremendous. For the mountains being cloven asunder, she presents to your eye, through the cleft, a small catch of smooth blue horizon, at an infinite distance in that plain country, inviting you, as it were, from the riot and tumult roaring around to pass through the breach and participate in the calm below. Here the eye ultimately composes itself; and that way, too, the road happens actually to lead. You cross the Patowmac above the junction, pass along its side through the base of the mountain for three miles, the terrible precipice hanging in fragments over you, and within about 20 miles reach Frederictown and the fine country around that. This scene is worth a voyage across the Atlantic."
SUBTITLE: The view of the Gap from Jefferson Rock
TITLE: The view from Jefferson Rock

DESCRIPTION: Lava Beds National Monument is a land of turmoil, both geological and historical. More than 700 caves, Native American rock art sites, historic battlefields and campsites, and a high desert wilderness experience await you!

DESCRIPTION: Timeline is a living history event with costumed volunteers portraying important figures from Lava Beds' colorful past. This year's living history groups ranged from the fur trappers of the 1800's to the early cave explorers of the 1900's. As part of the weekend's events, visitors were able to go on cave tours led by re-enactors of the cave pioneers JD Howard and EL Hopkins and attend a memorial ceremony for those killed in the Modoc War.

DESCRIPTION:
Park elevations range from 4,000 to 5,700 feet. Cold weather is possible any time of year, and snow has been recorded in all months. Winter day­time highs average 40°F; lows average 20°F. Morning fog is frequent from autumn through spring. Summer daytime highs average 75° to 80°F; lows average 50°F. Occasional thunderstorms occur in summer.

Although Lava Beds' weather is predictably unpredictable, the weather underground is mild all year round!
SUBTITLE: Cinder Butte in Snow
TITLE: Cinder Butte in Snow

DESCRIPTION: Petroglyph Point is an archaeological site within the Lava Beds National Monument.  Petroglyph Point contains one of the largest panels of Native American rock art in the United States.  The petroglyphs are carved along the face of a former island of ancient Tule Lake, in a region historically of the Modoc people territory.  The Petroglyph Point Archeological Site was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1975, while the Lava Beds National Monument Archeological District was listed in March 1991.  Most estimates date these carvings back between 2000 and 6000 years ago.
SUBTITLE: Petroglyph Point
TITLE: Petroglyph Point

DESCRIPTION:
In 1917, Spencer County's centennial commission requested the assistance of older residents from the county in determining the exact location of Thomas Lincoln's cabin.  Twenty such residents assembled on the historic property and pointed to a site they believed to be correct.  A marker was erected on the site on April 28, 1917.

In May, 1933, a Civilian Conservation Corps crew excavated 300 historic hearthstones, constructed a stone wall around the stone wall around the site.  In July 1935, a bronze casting in the shape of the historic cabin sill and hearth was placed on the site.

DESCRIPTION:
In 1847, present-day Atlanta was known as Marthasville. The population was approximately 500 and most of the inhabitants were employed by the Western and Atlantic Railroad. In 1848, the town was named Atlanta and in that same year the Atlanta City Council approved the organization of a volunteer fire brigade, which was the beginning of the modern-day Atlanta Fire Department.
 
As the city continued to grow the need for fire protection increased. Indeed, the expansion of the fire department kept pace with the growth of the city - a trend that still continues. The Atlanta Volunteer Fire Department had a long and interesting history and remained a vital part of the city until 1882 when the Atlanta Fire Department became official and the city council voted to pay salaries to all its firemen. 

No annals of a fire department would be complete without mentioning the important role that horses played in pulling the steamers and supply wagons. In 1867, two Norman horses were purchased by Fire Company Number 2 and a new era had arrived - the horse drawn fire engine. The horses were magnificent to watch and they knew their mission well. The smell of smoke would make them run faster to the source of the fire and the sight of flames didn't frighten them. As they galloped over the cobblestone streets sparks would shoot out as their steel shoes pounded against the stones. The horses were used for half-a-century before they gave way to mechanization. The last horse was retired in 1918. 

The first motorized pumping engine was placed in service in 1911 at Fire Station Number 12 on DeKalb Avenue. By 1914, the city purchased helmets, uniforms, rubber boots and coats for the firemen for the first time. The Atlanta Fire Department was integrated in 1963 when sixteen blacks were hired. They were all assigned to Fire Station Number 16 on Simpson Road. In 1977, seven female firefighters were hired.
SUBTITLE: 1927 LaFrance Fire Engine
TITLE: Fire Station No. 6

DESCRIPTION:
Ebenezer was founded in 1886, nine years after reconstruction began. A band of 13 faithful people united under the leadership of the Rev. John A. Parker.  Rev. Parker served as Ebenezer's first pastor at the original site on Airline Street from 1886 to 1894.
 
On March 14, 1894, the Rev. Adam Daniel Williams was called to pastor Ebenezer, a struggling church with seventeen members on the roll. During his first year as pastor he was responsible for adding approximately sixty-five members to the church. Rev. Williams liquidated the mortgage, purchased land near downtown Atlanta on McGruder Street and built a new church. With the continued growth of the congregation, the church on McGruder Street soon became too small. The membership moved their worship services to a storefront at 444 Edgewood Avenue while construction began on the Auburn Avenue site. The current church on Auburn Avenue was completed in 1922. 

As pastor of Ebenezer, Rev. A.D Williams promoted black businesses, urged his congregation to become home owners, and "get a piece of the turf." He led them in the battle for adequate public accommodations for blacks, despite Jim Crow segregation laws. Rev. Martin Luther King, Sr. served as assistant pastor to Rev. Williams from 1927 to 1930. Rev. King, Sr. became pastor of Ebenezer in 1931, following the death of Rev. Williams. 

During Rev. King, Sr. tenure as Pastor of Ebenezer he had three Co- pastors. In 1960 his oldest son, the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., joined his father as Co-Pastor, giving Ebenezer international stature. Following the assassination of Dr. King, Jr. on April 4, 1968, his younger son, the Rev. Alfred Daniel Williams King, replaced his brother as Ebenezer's second Co-Pastor. Rev. A. D. Kings tenure came to a close at his death in 1970, and was followed by Dr. Otis Moss in 1971. 

The Rev. Martin Luther King, Sr. retired on August 1, 1975 after forty-four years of tremendous service to Ebenezer and the world. Guided by Dr. King's suggestions, the congregation of Ebenezer called Dr. Joseph L. Roberts, Jr. to be its fourth Senior Pastor. Dr. Roberts retired in 2005.
SUBTITLE: Heritage Sanctuary of Ebenezer Baptist Church
TITLE: Historic Ebenezer Baptist Church

DESCRIPTION:
The International World Peace Rose Gardens program is a worldwide effort to help youth recognize the importance and value of peace. In March 1992, the Martin Luther King, Jr. World Peace Rose Garden was planted at the Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historic Site. The garden is an artistic interpretation of Dr. King's life and ideals of peace through nonviolence. The garden's "starburst" design brings attention to the brilliance of Dr. King's ideals using the Official Flower of the United States, the rose.

The Atlanta garden is one of five major World Peace Rose Gardens established around the world by International World Peace Rose Gardens. The other gardens are located at other cultural, historical and sacred centers of the world and focus on different aspects of peace.
SUBTITLE: International World Peace "I Have a Dream" Rose Garden
TITLE: International World Peace "I Have a Dream" Rose Garden

DESCRIPTION:
A staffed Information Desk is located just inside the front doors of the National Park Service Visitor Center. This is the place to stop for a brief orientation to the historic site, which facilities are open, how to sign up for a Birth Home tour, and where the nearest restroom is.

Located in the lobby of the Visitor Center is the "Children of Courage" exhibit, which is geared towards our younger visitors. This exhibit tells the story about the children of the Civil Rights Movement with a challenge to our youth today.

While in the Visitor Center don't miss the featured exhibit entitled "Courage To Lead" which follows the parallel paths of Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., and the Civil Rights Movement. Also, walk down "Freedom Road".

Video programs are presented in the Visitor Center Theater on a continuing basis.
SUBTITLE: Visitor Center at Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historic Site
TITLE: Visitor Center at Martin Luther King, Jr. National Historic Site

CREDITS: Photo: Linda Byers, Park Ranger, Martin Luther King, Jr., NHS
DESCRIPTION:
Birth Home Martin Luther King, Jr. was born January 15, 1929 at 501 Auburn Avenue, the home of his maternal grandparents.   For the next twelve years he lived here with his grandparents, parents, siblings, other family members and boarders.

Birth Home Tour   

Visiting the home where Dr. King was born and lived the first twelve years of his life is often the highlight of ones visit to the National Historic Site. Unfortunately trying to visit the Birth Home can also be the biggest letdown if you can't get on a tour. By following the instructions below and with a little luck you may get on a tour of the home on your first visit to the site. 

The home was built in 1895 and is on the National Register of Historic Places. The National Park Service (NPS) is steward of this most significant cultural resource.  The NPS is required to employ the most effective concepts and techniques to protect the resource against overuse and deterioration without compromising the integrity of the resource.   For these reasons, tours of the Birth Home are limited.


The Park Ranger led tour is FREE and lasts approximately 30 minutes during which time you will learn about the life of a young M. L. King. The home is open for tours on a daily basis, except Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day, with the first tour at 10:00 am and the last tour beginning at 4:30 p.m.  The tours begin every hour on the hour and are limited to 15 people per tour. 

The tours are filled on a first-come, first-served basis on the day of the tour.  No advanced registration or phone reservations are accepted. Upon arriving at the National Historic Site you should first proceed to the Visitor Center at 450 Auburn Avenue, NE to sign up for a tour. Before signing up for your tour you will be advised as to when the time of the next available tour.  You may sign-up for that tour or any later tour that may be open.  If there is an available tour you will be issued tickets and instructed on where to meet the park ranger conducting the tour.  Should you sign-up for a tour and find that you can not stay please notify a park ranger.  Once you are signed up feel free to visit the rest of the National Historic Site while waiting for your tour.  All other facilities are viewed on a self-guided basis. 

Groups (school, family reunion, youth, etc.) are limited to signing up for only 3 tour times per day for a total of 45 people. After signing up a group, the group leader is responsible dividing up the group and seeing that the people arrive for their tour on time.
SUBTITLE: Birth Home of Martin Luther King, Jr.
TITLE: Birth Home of Martin Luther King, Jr.

DESCRIPTION: Access was restricted to the Delta-01 Launch Control Facility from 1963 until 1991, when staff inside were responsible for the security, operation, and potential launching of ten Minuteman missiles in western South Dakota. Each missile contained a 1.2 megaton nuclear warhead, equal in destructive power to 1/3 of all ordinance used in WWII (including both atom bombs). Visitors can now tour a deactivated underground Launch Control Center and visit a missile silo with a missile on display in its historic state.

DESCRIPTION: Designed to aid navigation on the Mississippi River between St. Paul and Minneapolis, the Meeker Lock and Dam was quickly outmoded by the development of hydroelectric power, which required a taller dam. Lock and Dam 1, downstream from Meeker, was rebuilt tall enough to produce electricity, but in doing so raised the level of the river over the top of the Meeker Lock and Dam. Engineers then destroyed the upper several feet of the Meeker Dam so it wouldn't hinder navigation. Today, only the lock wall can be seen during low water.

DESCRIPTION: Coyotes are the most common desert predator mammal living in the monument. Their populations have declined over the past decade due to rapid city development on Albuquerque's Westside and the regional drought. It is rare to see such healthy coyotes in the park so if you are lucky enough to see one or two during your visit, snap a photo but do not attempt to approach them. Remember that coyotes are wild animals and will defend themselves if they feel threatened.
SUBTITLE: Coyotes patrolling their territory.
TITLE: Coyotes

DESCRIPTION:
The Western Diamondback rattlesnake is one of three venomous species found in the monument. Large male adults can reach 6 feet in length although the average size ranges from 3 to 4 feet. Rattlesnakes are members of the pit viper family, named so because they have a pair of pits between their eyes and nostrils. The pits function as heat receptors that allow the snake to strike accurately at their prey, even in complete darkness. Desert cottontail rabbits, mice, wood and kangaroo rats easily succumb to the venom within a few minutes. They may run a short distance before they collapse. The snake then tracks them down and swallows them whole.

The Western Diamondback rattlesnake is brownish to grayish in color with a row of dark diamonds with light borders running down its back. The last 2 to 4 inches of the tail have a series of evenly spaced white and black rings, commonly known as the rattle, which when vibrated by the snake makes that unforgettable rattling. Once you hear it, you'll never forget it.
SUBTITLE: Western Diamondback Rattlesnake relaxing in the shade.
TITLE: Western Diamondback Rattlesnake

DESCRIPTION: All it takes is a little rain for the grasses and shrubs to sprout new growth and green up the monument. JA volcano is one of 5 cinder cones protected within the monument. The small volcanic field here erupted along a fissure six different times over 200,000 years ago. Today, there are trails that walk you around the base of each cinder cone. Trail lengths vary from 1 mile to 4 miles roundtrip. This is an undeveloped area. No water is available. Vault restroom facilities are available. This area is open daily from 9:00 am to 5:00 pm daily.
SUBTITLE: A view of JA volcano after a weeks worth of summer rains.

DESCRIPTION:
Located at the Au Sable Point, 12 miles west (drive) of Grand Marais to the Hurricane River Campground then 1.5 miles (walk) east.

In 1872, Congress appropriated $40,000 to build at lighthouse at Au Sable Point. The light station began operation on August 19, 1874. The light tower is 86 feet high, and shines its beacon 18 miles out on Lake Superior. 

In 1958, the Coast Guard converted the light station to an automatic unattended light, and discontinued the fog signal.

DESCRIPTION: No military campaign had more influence on the course of the Civil War than a series of engagements, known collectively as the Seven Days' battles. Today Richmond National Battlefield Park owns only 60 acres of the Gaines' Mill battlefield—the largest battle of the entire Seven Days—including the spot where John B. Hood's Confederates achieved the first breakthrough in the Union line. The site is criss-crossed with walking trails and interpretive signs. The historic Watt House, centerpiece to the battlefield, still stands but is not open to the public.
SUBTITLE: A cannon in a field, a white house and trees in the background
TITLE: Gaines' Mill Battlefield

DESCRIPTION:
As capital of the newly formed Confederate States of America, Richmond, Virginia, became the constant target of northern armies. The key to the city's river defenses lay in a small fort only seven miles south of the capital: Drewry's Bluff. 

On May 15, 1862, a Federal squadron steamed around the bend in the river below Drewry's Bluff.  The squadron opened fire on Drewry's Bluff.  When Confederate batteries in the fort replied, the whole vicinity shook with the concussion of the big guns. Southern infantry lined the banks of the river to harass the sailors. 

After four long hours of exchanging fire, the "perfect tornado of shot and shell" ended. Federal sailors suffered at least 14 dead and 13 wounded, while the Confederates admitted to 7 killed and 8 wounded. The massive fort on Drewry's Bluff had blunted the Union advance just seven miles short of the Confederate capital. Richmond remained safe.

Drewry's Bluff is one of the 13 units that Richmond National Battlefied park preserves.
SUBTITLE: A cannon on a bluff overlooking the James River
TITLE: Drewry's Bluff

DESCRIPTION: Tredegar Iron Works was an iron foundry during the Civil War and produced more than 1000 field and siege cannons during the war. Today, Tredegar Iron Works serves as the main visitor center for Richmond National Battlefield Park. The site introduces visitors to the city of Richmond and the two military campaigns fought around the city- the 1862 Peninsula Campaign and the 1864 Overland Campaign. Exhibits on the 3rd floor discuss the military and home front throughout the war
SUBTITLE: A three story brick Iron foundry in the background, a large black cannon in the foreground
TITLE: Tredegar Iron Works

DESCRIPTION:
Elk Mountain Campground is a quiet place located on the edge of the prairie.  Campers can find campsites in the forest or the open prairie.  The campground has 65 sites and is open all year, weather permitting.  Occupancy is on a first-come, first-served basis; however the campground rarely fills.  

In the warmer months, the campground has restrooms with cold water and flush toilets but no showers, electrical hook-ups, or dump stations.  During the off-season the facilities are limited with only vault toilets. Firewood is available for campers.  Two sites are available for campers with disabilities.

TITLE: Campsite in Elk Mountain Campground

DESCRIPTION:

Occupancy is on a first-come, first-served basis; however the campground rarely fills.  Each site accommodates up to eight people.  Two sites are available for campers with disabilities.

Group camping is available by reservation.  For group reservations call the park at 605-745-4600.

In the summer the campground has restrooms with cold water and flush toilets but no showers, electrical hook-ups, or dump stations.  During the colder months the water is turned off and vault toilets are available.  Firewood is available for campers.

DESCRIPTION:
Experience the cave by candlelight. This tour takes place in a less developed, unlighted part of the cave similar to tours given in the 1890s. Each participant will carry a candle bucket. 

Because this tour is mostly on unpaved, unlighted trail shoes with non-slip soles are required. No sandals! This tour is limited to 10 people and the minimum age is 8. This strenuous tour covers one mile of rugged trail and lasts 2 hours. The tour is only available in the summer season (mid-June through Labor Day) and pre-registration is strongly recommended. These arrangements may only be made by telephone, up to one month in advance of the tour - (605) 745-4600.
SUBTITLE: Tour Wind Cave by Candlelight
TITLE: Tour Wind Cave by Candlelight

DESCRIPTION: Visitors walk through the middle level of the cave where boxwork is abundant. This tour begins at the walk-in entrance and exits by elevator. This moderately strenuous, 1¼ hour tour has 300 stairs (mostly down).  All cave tours are ranger-guided and leave from the visitor center.
SUBTITLE: Walk through the cave on the Natural Entrance Cave Tour
TITLE: Walk through the cave on the Natural Entrance Cave Tour

DESCRIPTION:
While many speleothems have formed as water has dripped into the passages, the most conspicuous feature of Wind Cave, boxwork, has formed differently. Boxwork is found in small amounts in other caves, but perhaps in no other cave in the world is boxwork so well-formed and abundant as in Wind Cave. 

Boxwork is made of thin blades of calcite that project from cave walls and ceilings, forming a honeycomb pattern. The fins intersect one another at various angles, forming "boxes" on all cave surfaces. Boxwork is largely confined to middle layer of Wind Cave and easily seen on all tours.
SUBTITLE: Wind Cave's unique formation called boxwork is seen on the Natural Entrance Cave Tour
TITLE: Wind Cave's unique formation called boxwork seen on the Natural Entrance Cave Tour

DESCRIPTION: Boxwork is believed to be older than the cave itself.  Geologist believe the boxwork formed in tiny cracks in the limestone, then when the cave formed, the water was able to dissolve the limestone, but not able to dissolve the calcite crack fillings, exposing the boxwork that we see today.  This unusual feature is seen along all of the cave tours in Wind Cave.
SUBTITLE: Boxwork is abundant along the tours routes in Wind Cave
TITLE: Boxwork is abundant along the tours routes in Wind Cave

DESCRIPTION: The Fairgrounds Tour includes some of the larger rooms found in the developed area of the cave. Visitors will see examples of many cave formations, including Wind Cave boxwork, frostwork, popcorn, and a few fossils. The tour enters and exits the cave by elevator. This moderately strenuous tour has 450 stairs half up and half down with one flight of 90 step up, and lasts 1½ hours.  This tour is only available in the summer season - mid-June through Labor Day.
SUBTITLE: The Fairgrounds Tours also visit the upper layers of Wind Cave
TITLE: The Fairgrounds Tours also visit the upper layers of Wind Cave

DESCRIPTION: All of the major features of Wind Cave, including cave popcorn, boxwork, and flowstone are seen on this tour which enters and leaves the cave by elevator. This one hour tour is our least strenuous with 150 stairs - half up and half down.  This is a perfect tour for visitors with a limited amount of time or for people with limited abilities to negotiate steps.
SUBTITLE: Popcorn is seen along the Garden of Eden Cave Tour
TITLE: Popcorn is seen along the Garden of Eden Cave Tour

DESCRIPTION:
Explore the cave away from the developed trails. On this 4-hour tour visitors will be introduced to basic, safe caving. This tour is only available during the summer season - mid-June through Labor Day.

Wear old clothes and gloves, as much of the trip will be crawling. Long pants, long sleeved shirts and sturdy, lace up boots or shoes with non-slip soles are required. The park provides hard hats, lights, and kneepads. Please do not bring jewelry, watches, camera, and/or other valuables on the tour. This tour is limited to 10 people and the minimum age is 16. We require a signed consent form for those 17 and under. Pre-registration is required. Arrangements may only be made by telephone, up to one month in advance of the tour - (605) 745-4600.
SUBTITLE: The Wild Cave Tour (Spelunking) gives visitors the chance to meet the cave on its terms.
TITLE: The Wild Cave Tour (Spelunking) gives visitors the chance to meet the cave on its terms.

DESCRIPTION: Sharing the many unusual features of the cave with your children provides them the opportunity to enjoy our natural world in a safe environment.  Seeing the cave on a guided tour is an adventure your children will always remember.  You can even go beyond the normal tour and challenge yourselves on a more strenuous trip such as the Candlelight Tour (for youngsters 8 or older) or, for young adults 16 and older, the Wild Cave Tour.  Cave tours provide a great way to experience and learn about the underground world. National parks are special places protected for us and future generations to enjoy.  Enjoy the park and share those experiences with others.
SUBTITLE: Share the many unusual features of the cave with your children.
TITLE: Share the many unusual features of the cave with your children.

SUBTITLE: Declaration of Sentiments on a rock wall with water streaming over
TITLE: Declararion of Sentiments Waterwall

DESCRIPTION: Come stand face to face with courageous women and men! The life-size bronze statues, called "The First Wave," in the lobby of the park visitor center, depict the five women organizers of the First Women's Rights Convention. Statues of several men who attended and participated in the convention, women and children children surround the organizers. The convention was held in Seneca Falls, NY on July 19 and 20, 1848 and started the women's rights movement in America.
SUBTITLE: Life-size bronze statues depicting people in 1848 in the lobby of the visitor center
TITLE: "The First Wave" Statues

DESCRIPTION: Park Ranger John Stoudt discusses the early women's rights movement with a group of visitors in the visitor center.
SUBTITLE: Park Ranger John Stoudt stands in the middle of a group of visitors in the park visitor center.
TITLE: Park Ranger John Stoudt with visitors

DESCRIPTION: On July 16, 1848 Elizabeth Cady Stanton met with the M'Clintock family in the front parlor of this house and together they wrote the first draft of the Declaration of Sentiments. The Declaration of Sentiments is one of America's founding documents of democracy. It was edited again on July 19, 1848 at the First Women's Rights Convention, with the final version discussed on the second day, July 20, 1848. The document paraphrases the Declaration of Sentiments and demands equal rights for women as citizens.
SUBTITLE: The two-story red brick M'Clintock House from the front.
TITLE: M'Clintock House

DESCRIPTION: Elizabeth Cady owned this farmhouse on the edge of Seneca Falls, New York from 1847-1863. She named her property "Grassmere," and often referred to it as "the center of the rebellion." She raised seven children here, with the four youngest born in an upstairs bedroom. Her husband Henry B. Stanton made sure that when the deed was registered in the courthouse that his wife was listed as the owner. Some suggest that property ownership and being levied taxes without the right to vote or "taxation without representation" was one of the reasons Elizabeth Cady Stanton began her career in women's rights while in Seneca Falls.
SUBTITLE: White two story wooded framed house with green shutters.
TITLE: Elizabeth Cady Stanton House

DESCRIPTION: The First Women's Rights Convention was held in the Wesleyan Chapel on July 19 and 20, 1848. The convention was called and organized by five housewives who were active in anti-slavery and human rights reform. Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Lucretia Mott, Mary Ann M'Clintock, Martha Wright, and Jane Hunt challenged the current ideas of womanhood, citizenship, personal liberty, legal and religious rights, custody and marriage rights, and equal pay - all with ten days to prepare. The ideas expressed at the convention started "the second revolution in America."
SUBTITLE: Wesleyan Chapel from the front.
TITLE: Wesleyan Chapel

DESCRIPTION: The World War II Memorial was dedicated in 2004.
